## 2. System Architecture

### 2.1 High-Level Architecture

HackXHarder follows a decoupled architecture: a Next.js frontend communicates with a Django REST Framework backend over a versioned JSON API. PostgreSQL is the system of record; Redis backs caching, rate limiting, and background task queues.

```text
                        ┌─────────────────────────┐
                        │   Next.js Frontend      │
                        │   (Researcher / Company │
                        │    / Triage / Admin UI)  │
                        └────────────┬────────────┘
                                     │ HTTPS / REST (JSON)
                                     │ JWT Bearer Auth
                        ┌────────────▼────────────┐
                        │  Django REST Framework  │
                        │  - Auth & Permissions    │
                        │  - Business Logic        │
                        │  - Serializers / ViewSets│
                        └──┬──────────┬───────────┘
                           │          │
                  ┌────────▼──┐   ┌───▼─────────┐
                  │ PostgreSQL │   │    Redis     │
                  │ (primary   │   │ (cache, rate │
                  │  datastore)│   │ limit, Celery│
                  └────────────┘   │   broker)    │
                                    └───┬──────────┘
                                        │
                              ┌─────────▼─────────┐
                              │  Celery Workers     │
                              │  - Email notif.      │
                              │  - Report scoring    │
                              │  - Scheduled jobs    │
                              └──────────────────────┘

        External services: S3-compatible object storage (report attachments),
        SMTP/transactional email, SSLCommerz / bKash / Nagad (rewards payout).
```

### 2.2 Technology Stack

| Layer | Technology | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Frontend | Next.js 15 (App Router) | Server components for public pages; client components for dashboards |
| Backend API | Django 5 + Django REST Framework | ViewSets + routers, versioned at `/api/v1/` |
| Database | PostgreSQL 15+ | Primary relational store; JSONB for flexible scope/rules fields |
| Cache / Queue Broker | Redis 7+ | Cache, login rate limiting, Celery broker/result backend |
| Async Tasks | Celery + Celery Beat | Email, notifications, scheduled SLA checks |
| Auth | JWT (SimpleJWT) with refresh rotation | Session-based fallback for admin Django panel only |
| File Storage | S3-compatible (e.g., DigitalOcean Spaces / AWS S3) | Report attachments, never served from app servers directly |
| Search (optional, post-MVP) | PostgreSQL full-text or Meilisearch | Program and report search |

### 2.3 Environment Topology

- **Development** — local Docker Compose: Django, Postgres, Redis, Celery worker, Next.js dev server.
- **Staging** — mirrors production infra at smaller scale; used for QA and client demos.
- **Production** — containerized deployment (Docker + a process manager such as Gunicorn/Uvicorn behind Nginx), PostgreSQL managed instance, Redis managed instance, S3-compatible storage, separate Celery worker and beat containers.

