## 6. Vulnerability Report Lifecycle

### 6.1 Workflow Diagram

```text
Researcher submits report
        │
        ▼
   status = NEW  ──────────────► Triage reviews
                                       │
                       ┌───────────────┼────────────────┐
                       ▼               ▼                ▼
                  NOT_APPLICABLE   DUPLICATE      NEEDS_MORE_INFO
                  / INFORMATIVE    (linked to            │
                  / OUT_OF_SCOPE   original)        researcher replies
                  (terminal)       (terminal)             │
                                                           ▼
                                                    back to NEW/TRIAGED
                       │
                       ▼ (valid)
                   TRIAGED ──► forwarded to company
                       │
                       ▼
                   ACCEPTED ──► company fixes the issue
                       │
                       ▼
                  RETESTING ──► researcher / triage retest
                       │
                       ▼
                  RESOLVED
                       │
                       ▼
             REWARD_APPROVED ──► payout processed
                       │
                       ▼
                    PAID
                       │
                       ▼
                   CLOSED

  Any state can transition to DISPUTED if the researcher contests
  a decision; a platform_admin resolves disputes manually.
```

### 6.2 Report Status List

| Status | Meaning | Terminal? |
|---|---|---|
| `new` | Just submitted, awaiting triage | No |
| `needs_more_information` | Triage requested clarification from researcher | No |
| `triaged` | Validated as a real, in-scope issue; forwarded to company | No |
| `accepted` | Company has acknowledged and is working a fix | No |
| `duplicate` | Matches an existing report | Yes |
| `informative` | Valid observation, not a security risk requiring a fix | Yes |
| `not_applicable` | Not a valid vulnerability | Yes |
| `out_of_scope` | Target/asset was not covered by the program scope | Yes |
| `retesting` | Fix deployed; awaiting confirmation | No |
| `resolved` | Fix confirmed effective | No |
| `reward_approved` | Company/triage approved a reward amount | No |
| `paid` | Reward payout completed | No |
| `closed` | Report fully closed out | Yes |
| `disputed` | Researcher has contested a decision | No (until resolved) |

### 6.3 State Machine Implementation Notes

- Implement transitions as an explicit allow-list (e.g., a dict mapping `current_status → [allowed_next_statuses]`), not free-form status writes. Reject any transition not in the allow-list with HTTP 400.
- Every transition must write a `ReportStatusHistory` row in the same database transaction as the status update.
- Only `triage_analyst` and `platform_admin` can move a report into `triaged`, `duplicate`, `informative`, `not_applicable`, or `out_of_scope`.
- Only `company_admin`/`company_member` (with triage oversight) can move a report into `accepted` or `resolved`.
- Reward-related transitions (`reward_approved`, `paid`) require a non-null `Reward` record with a matching status.

---

## 7. API Specification

Base URL: `/api/v1/`. All endpoints return JSON. All list endpoints are paginated using `limit`/`offset` query parameters and return `{ count, next, previous, results }`. Authenticated endpoints require `Authorization: Bearer <access_token>`.

### 7.1 Authentication

**`POST /api/v1/auth/register/`**

Registers a new user. Role defaults to `researcher`; company registration uses a separate endpoint that also creates a `CompanyProfile`.

```text
Request body:
{
  "email": "user@example.com",       // required
  "password": "string",              // required, min 12 chars
  "role": "researcher"               // required: researcher | company_admin
}

Response 201:
{
  "id": "uuid",
  "email": "user@example.com",
  "role": "researcher"
}
```

**`POST /api/v1/auth/login/`**

```text
Request body:
{ "email": "user@example.com", "password": "string" }

Response 200:
{
  "access": "jwt...",
  "refresh": "jwt...",
  "user": { "id": "uuid", "role": "researcher" }
}

Response 401: { "detail": "Invalid credentials" }
Note: rate-limited (see Section 9.4).
```

**`POST /api/v1/auth/refresh/`**

```text
Request body: { "refresh": "jwt..." }
Response 200: { "access": "jwt..." }
```

**`POST /api/v1/auth/2fa/verify/`**

Required step after login for `company_admin` and `platform_admin` accounts before a usable access token is issued.

### 7.2 Researcher Profile

| Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|
| `GET /api/v1/researchers/me/` | Get the authenticated researcher's profile |
| `PATCH /api/v1/researchers/me/` | Update bio, skill_tags, display_name |
| `GET /api/v1/researchers/{id}/` | Public profile view (reputation, badges, public stats) |

### 7.3 Companies

| Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|
| `POST /api/v1/companies/register/` | Register a new company; creates CompanyProfile + owner User |
| `GET /api/v1/companies/me/` | Get the authenticated company's profile |
| `PATCH /api/v1/companies/me/` | Update company profile fields |
| `POST /api/v1/companies/me/team/` | Invite a company_member to the team |
| `GET /api/v1/companies/me/analytics/` | Dashboard metrics: open reports, avg. resolution time, spend |

### 7.4 Programs

| Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|
| `GET /api/v1/programs/` | List public, approved programs (filterable by program_type, severity range) |
| `GET /api/v1/programs/{id}/` | Program detail including scope and reward table |
| `POST /api/v1/programs/` | Create a draft program (company_admin only) |
| `PATCH /api/v1/programs/{id}/` | Update a draft/approved program (owner company only) |
| `POST /api/v1/programs/{id}/submit-for-approval/` | Move status draft → pending_approval |
| `POST /api/v1/programs/{id}/approve/` | Admin-only: pending_approval → approved |
| `POST /api/v1/programs/{id}/scope/` | Add a ScopeAsset entry |
| `POST /api/v1/programs/{id}/reward-tiers/` | Define/update RewardTier rows |

**Example: `GET /api/v1/programs/{id}/`**

```text
Response 200:
{
  "id": "uuid",
  "title": "Acme Corp Bug Bounty",
  "program_type": "bbp",
  "status": "approved",
  "description": "...",
  "rules": "...",
  "safe_harbor_policy": "...",
  "scope": {
    "in_scope": [{ "asset_type": "domain", "asset_value": "*.acme.com" }],
    "out_of_scope": [{ "asset_type": "domain", "asset_value": "blog.acme.com" }]
  },
  "reward_tiers": [
    { "severity": "critical", "min_amount": "20000.00", "max_amount": "100000.00" },
    { "severity": "high", "min_amount": "10000.00", "max_amount": "50000.00" }
  ]
}
```

### 7.5 Vulnerability Reports

| Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|
| `POST /api/v1/reports/` | Submit a new report (researcher only) |
| `GET /api/v1/reports/` | List reports scoped to the caller's role (own reports / own program / assigned) |
| `GET /api/v1/reports/{id}/` | Report detail (object-level permission enforced) |
| `PATCH /api/v1/reports/{id}/status/` | Transition report status (allow-listed transitions only) |
| `POST /api/v1/reports/{id}/comments/` | Add a comment (is_internal flag for triage/company-only notes) |
| `POST /api/v1/reports/{id}/attachments/` | Upload a file attachment (multipart/form-data) |
| `GET /api/v1/reports/{id}/history/` | Full ReportStatusHistory for the report |

**Example: `POST /api/v1/reports/`**

```text
Request body:
{
  "program_id": "uuid",                       // required
  "title": "SQL Injection in /api/search",     // required
  "description": "...",                       // required
  "steps_to_reproduce": "...",                 // required
  "affected_asset": "api.acme.com/search",     // required
  "severity": "high"                           // required, researcher's initial estimate
}

Response 201:
{ "id": "uuid", "status": "new", "submitted_at": "2026-06-24T10:00:00Z" }

Response 429: rate limited (see Section 9.4)
```

### 7.6 Triage

| Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|
| `GET /api/v1/triage/queue/` | Reports with status=new awaiting review, sorted by SLA risk |
| `POST /api/v1/triage/reports/{id}/assign/` | Self-assign or assign to another triage_analyst |
| `PATCH /api/v1/triage/reports/{id}/severity/` | Adjust severity from the researcher's initial estimate |
| `POST /api/v1/triage/reports/{id}/mark-duplicate/` | Link to an existing report; sets status=duplicate |
| `POST /api/v1/triage/reports/{id}/recommend-reward/` | Suggest a reward amount within the program's tier range |

### 7.7 Rewards

| Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|
| `GET /api/v1/rewards/wallet/` | Researcher's wallet balance and reward history |
| `POST /api/v1/rewards/{report_id}/approve/` | Company approves the reward amount |
| `POST /api/v1/rewards/{report_id}/payout/` | Trigger payout via configured gateway (admin/company) |
| `GET /api/v1/rewards/{report_id}/` | Reward detail and payout status |

### 7.8 Admin

| Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|
| `GET /api/v1/admin/companies/pending/` | Companies awaiting verification |
| `POST /api/v1/admin/companies/{id}/approve/` | Approve or reject a company |
| `GET /api/v1/admin/programs/pending/` | Programs awaiting approval |
| `GET /api/v1/admin/disputes/` | List open disputes |
| `POST /api/v1/admin/disputes/{id}/resolve/` | Resolve a dispute with a final decision |
| `GET /api/v1/admin/audit-logs/` | Searchable audit trail |

### 7.9 Standard Error Format

```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "REPORT_INVALID_TRANSITION",
    "message": "Cannot move report from 'duplicate' to 'accepted'.",
    "field_errors": {}
  }
}
```

---

## 8. Severity & Reward Reference

### 8.1 Severity Levels

| Severity | Description |
|---|---|
| Critical | Vulnerability that can fully compromise system, data, or users |
| High | Serious vulnerability with major business or technical impact |
| Medium | Moderate risk vulnerability requiring valid conditions |
| Low | Minor vulnerability with limited impact |
| Informational | Security observation or best-practice issue |

### 8.2 Default Bounty Reward Range (BDT)

| Severity | Reward Range |
|---|---|
| Critical | 20,000 – 100,000 BDT |
| High | 10,000 – 50,000 BDT |
| Medium | 3,000 – 20,000 BDT |
| Low | 500 – 5,000 BDT |
| Informational | Points only or no reward |

These ranges are platform defaults shown to companies when creating a program; each company can override them per program via RewardTier records, within platform-defined min/max guardrails to prevent abuse.

---

## 9. Security Requirements

HackXHarder stores sensitive, pre-disclosure vulnerability information. A breach of this platform would itself be a serious security incident affecting every client company. Security is not a post-MVP feature — the items below are mandatory for the MVP release.

### 9.1 Transport & Session Security

- Enforce HTTPS everywhere; HTTP requests redirect to HTTPS at the load balancer/Nginx layer.
- Set `Strict-Transport-Security`, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options`, and a restrictive `Content-Security-Policy`.
- JWT access tokens short-lived (15 minutes); refresh tokens rotated on use and revocable server-side (store refresh token IDs, not just trust the JWT signature).
- Two-factor authentication required for `company_admin` and `platform_admin` roles; recommended for researcher accounts.

### 9.2 Authentication & Password Policy

- Minimum 12-character passwords; check against a breached-password list (e.g., via the Pwned Passwords API range query) at registration and password change.
- Passwords hashed with Argon2 or PBKDF2 (Django's default), never stored or logged in plaintext.
- Account lockout / exponential backoff after repeated failed login attempts, tracked per-account and per-IP in Redis.

### 9.3 Authorization & Data Isolation

- Every object-level endpoint must verify ownership/role at the query level (filter querysets by request.user's role and related IDs), not just at the URL/view level — this is the platform's primary defense against IDOR.
- Vulnerability reports are private by default: visible only to the submitting researcher, the owning company's team, assigned triage analysts, and platform admins.
- Internal triage notes (`is_internal=true` comments) must never be serialized into a researcher-facing API response, even if the researcher requests the report by ID.

### 9.4 Rate Limiting

| Endpoint / Action | Suggested Limit |
|---|---|
| `POST /auth/login/` | 5 attempts / 15 minutes per IP + per account |
| `POST /auth/register/` | 10 / hour per IP |
| `POST /reports/` (submission) | 20 / hour per researcher account |
| `POST /reports/{id}/comments/` | 60 / hour per account |
| File attachment upload | 30 / hour per account |

Implement using Redis-backed counters (e.g., django-ratelimit or a custom DRF throttle class). Return HTTP 429 with a `Retry-After` header on limit breach.

### 9.5 File Upload Validation

- Validate file extension and MIME type against an explicit allow-list (e.g., png, jpg, pdf, txt, log, zip up to a defined size cap).
- Re-derive the content type from file bytes server-side (do not trust the client-supplied Content-Type header).
- Store all attachments in S3-compatible object storage outside the web root; serve via signed, time-limited URLs — never serve uploaded files directly from an application server path.
- Run uploaded files through an antivirus/malware scan (e.g., ClamAV) asynchronously via Celery; mark `scanned_status` accordingly and block download until scanned.

### 9.6 Standard Web Vulnerability Defenses

| Threat | Primary Defense |
|---|---|
| SQL Injection | Django ORM / parameterized queries only; no raw SQL string interpolation |
| XSS | Next.js auto-escaping by default; sanitize any HTML the frontend renders from user content; strict CSP |
| CSRF | JWT bearer auth for the API (not cookie-based) removes most CSRF risk; if cookies are used anywhere (e.g., Django admin), enable Django's CSRF middleware |
| SSRF | Never let server-side code fetch arbitrary user-supplied URLs (e.g., for link previews) without an allow-list and internal-IP blocking |
| IDOR | Object-level permission checks on every queryset (see Section 9.3) |
| Mass assignment | Explicit serializer fields (`fields = [...]`) — never serializers using `fields = '__all__'` on writable endpoints |

### 9.7 Logging, Auditing & Backups

- All admin, triage, and company actions that change state are written to `AuditLogEntry` inside the same transaction as the change.
- Application logs must never contain passwords, tokens, full report bodies, or unredacted PII; use structured logging with explicit allow-listed fields.
- Automated, encrypted, daily PostgreSQL backups with tested restore procedure; retain at minimum 30 days.
- Centralized log aggregation with alerting on repeated authentication failures, privilege escalation attempts, and unusual admin activity.

### 9.8 Sensitive Data Handling

- Encrypt sensitive fields at rest where the database-level encryption is insufficient (e.g., payout account details) using application-level field encryption.
- Apply data retention rules: closed reports and associated PII should have a defined retention/anonymization policy in line with applicable data protection requirements.

> **Pre-Launch Security Checklist**
> - Run an authenticated penetration test against staging before public launch — this platform's own credibility depends on practicing what it sells.
> - Confirm object-level permission tests exist for every report, program, and reward endpoint, with automated tests for cross-tenant access attempts.
> - Confirm rate limiting is active in production config (not only in code) before go-live.

---

## 10. MVP Build Plan

### 10.1 MVP Scope

The MVP focuses on proving the core loop: a company can publish a program, a researcher can submit a report against it, and that report can move through a status pipeline to resolution — with the minimum security baseline from Section 9 fully in place from day one.

- User registration and login (JWT)
- Role-based dashboard (researcher / company / admin)
- Researcher profile
- Company profile + admin company approval
- Program creation + program approval
- Public program listing + program detail page
- Vulnerability report submission
- Report inbox + report detail page
- Comment system
- Report status update (allow-listed transitions)
- Basic reward amount field (manual, no payment gateway yet)
- Email notification on status change
- Basic admin dashboard

### 10.2 Suggested Sprint Breakdown (8 Weeks)

| Sprint | Focus | Key Deliverables |
|---|---|---|
| Sprint 1 (Wk 1-2) | Foundations | Project scaffolding, accounts app, JWT auth, role model, CI pipeline |
| Sprint 2 (Wk 3-4) | Company & Program | companies + programs apps, admin approval flows, public program listing |
| Sprint 3 (Wk 5-6) | Reports Core | reports app, status state machine, comments, basic attachment upload |
| Sprint 4 (Wk 7) | Rewards & Notifications | Manual reward field, Celery email notifications, researcher dashboard |
| Sprint 5 (Wk 8) | Admin & Hardening | Admin dashboard, audit logging, rate limiting, security pass, staging deploy |

### 10.3 Post-MVP Roadmap

1. Private bug bounty programs and researcher invitation system
2. CVSS calculator integrated into report submission
3. Automated duplicate detection (text similarity on title/description/affected_asset)
4. SLA tracking dashboards driven by ReportStatusHistory timestamps
5. Public disclosure reports (opt-in, post-resolution)
6. Researcher badges and monthly leaderboard
7. Payment gateway integration: SSLCommerz, then bKash/Nagad direct payout
8. Jira / GitHub integration for company-side remediation tracking
9. AI-assisted report quality checks and duplicate-report flagging
10. Mobile app (researcher-focused: submission and status tracking on the go)
11. Organization team management (multiple admins, granular company-side roles)
12. Compliance reporting exports for enterprise clients

---

## 11. Appendix

### 11.1 Glossary

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| VDP | Vulnerability Disclosure Program — responsible disclosure without a guaranteed reward |
| BBP | Bug Bounty Program — reward-based program |
| Triage | The validation step between report submission and company review |
| Scope | The defined set of assets a researcher is authorized to test |
| Safe Harbor | Legal assurance protecting researchers who test within the defined scope and rules |
| IDOR | Insecure Direct Object Reference — an authorization flaw allowing access to objects by guessing/altering an identifier |
| SLA | Service Level Agreement — target time-to-respond/resolve commitments |

### 11.2 Open Questions for Product/Engineering Alignment

- Final payout flow: does the platform hold researcher funds in escrow, or does the company pay out directly with the platform only recording the transaction?
- KYC requirements for researcher payouts above a certain threshold, given Bangladesh financial regulations.
- Whether triage is an in-house platform team or whether companies may opt into self-triage for the MVP.
- Data residency requirements if any client company requires in-country data storage.

